Create the Node.js backend context once in a server-only module and reuse it for all routes/jobs.

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});

process.once("SIGTERM", async () => {
  await jazz.shutdown();
  process.exit(0);
});
```

Install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency. Use a stable `dataPath` for durable local state; `{ type: "memory" }` is only safe with an upstream `serverUrl`. Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and never public-prefixed. Use `backendSecret` when connected backends need `asBackend`, `forRequest`, `forSession`, or attribution handles. Await the required write durability tier before returning success from endpoints that promise persisted or globally visible writes.

When query inputs are reactive, pass an accessor/factory so the binding rebuilds the query when inputs change.

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
  import { app } from "./schema";

  export let projectId: string | undefined;

  const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
    projectId ? app.todos.where({ projectId }).orderBy("title", "asc") : undefined,
  );
</script>
```

```tsx
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: projectId()
    ? app.todos.where({ projectId: projectId()! }).orderBy("title", "asc")
    : undefined,
}));
```

Do not build the query once outside the accessor if `projectId` can change.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two optimistic UI writes that should appear locally together after the callback commits.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the writes must remain staged until authority acceptance and then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Use Jazz’s Rust API as a dynamic row boundary, then convert immediately into strict app types.

Define schema with `SchemaBuilder` / `TableSchema::builder`, query with `QueryBuilder`, and treat `JazzClient::query(...)` results as `(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)`. Keep each projection next to one decoder:

```rust
struct TodoRow {
    id: ObjectId,
    title: String,
    done: bool,
    description: Option<String>,
}

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if values.len() != 3 {
        return Err(AppError::Schema("todos projection changed"));
    }

    let title = match &values[0] {
        Value::Text(v) => v.clone(),
        _ => return Err(AppError::Schema("todos.title must be text")),
    };

    let done = match values[1] {
        Value::Boolean(v) => v,
        _ => return Err(AppError::Schema("todos.done must be boolean")),
    };

    let description = match &values[2] {
        Value::Text(v) => Some(v.clone()),
        Value::Null => None,
        _ => return Err(AppError::Schema("todos.description must be text or null")),
    };

    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```

For writes, use `row_input!` for inserts and public `insert`, `update`, `delete`, or transaction APIs. Do not invent generated Rust table handles. If the caller needs committed behavior, keep the returned `BatchId` and await `wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer)` or `GlobalServer` with an application timeout.

Create one long-lived backend `JazzClient` at service startup using `AppContext` with persistent storage and backend credentials. Per request, authenticate the caller, derive a stable Jazz `Session`, then scope the client with `client.for_session(session)` so reads, writes, permissions, and authorship all run as the caller.

Endpoint shape:

```rust
async fn update_todo(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    auth: CallerAuth,
    Path(id): Path<ObjectId>,
    Json(body): Json<UpdateTodoBody>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, AppError> {
    let session = state.auth.verify(auth).await?;
    let db = state.jazz.for_session(session);

    let batch_id = db.update(id, vec![
        ("done".into(), Value::Boolean(body.done)),
    ])?;

    tokio::time::timeout(
        state.write_timeout,
        db.wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer),
    )
    .await
    .map_err(|_| AppError::DurabilityTimeout)??;

    let rows = db.query(todo_by_id_query(id)).await?;
    let row = rows.into_iter().next().ok_or(AppError::NotFound)?;

    Ok(Json(decode_todo(row.0, &row.1)?))
}
```

Map failures deliberately: invalid auth to `401`, invalid input to `400`/`422`, absent or policy-filtered rows to `404`, policy rejection to `403`, durability timeout/disconnect to `503`/`504`, and decoder/schema mismatch to a safe internal error. Do not return raw `JazzError` strings to clients.

Use a real local server and two memory clients. After Alice writes rows, wait for edge durability, then let Bob poll until he can observe them. Do not assert raw query order; normalize by a stable field.

```ts
it("syncs several todos without depending on query order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  const clients: Db[] = [];

  try {
    await deploy({
      serverUrl: server.url,
      appId: server.appId,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      schema: app,
      permissions,
    });

    const alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
    const bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
    clients.push(alice, bob);

    await Promise.all([
      alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "B", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "A", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "C", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ]);

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
      const titles = rows.map((row) => row.title).sort();
      expect(titles).toEqual(["A", "B", "C"]);
    });
  } finally {
    await Promise.all(clients.map((db) => db.shutdown()));
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

Use `createPolicyTestApp` so the test exercises the public policy surface. Assert denied reads as absent rows, and denied writes with `expectDenied`.

```ts
it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);

  try {
    const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
    const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

    const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice private todo", done: false }).value;

    await expect(alice.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id }))).resolves.toHaveLength(1);
    await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

    bob.expectDenied((db) =>
      db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Bob should not write" }),
    );

    alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
      db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Alice can still write" }),
    );
  } finally {
    await testApp.shutdown();
  }
});
```
